                        <p>
                            The most emblematic musical genres of Taza include Berber music, closely connected to the Amazigh culture of the region. Berber songs are often accompanied by traditional instruments such as the "guembri," a three-stringed lute, and the "bendir," a frame drum. Enchanting melodies and captivating rhythms take listeners on a journey through time, celebrating ancestral traditions and stories passed down from generation to generation.

                            Furthermore, Taza is also influenced by Arab-Andalusian music, adding an additional dimension to its musical heritage. These refined melodies, inherited from the period of Arab-Andalusian influence in Morocco, are played during special ceremonies and religious festivities, adding an elegant and sophisticated touch to these occasions.

                            Over time, Taza's musical heritage has been enriched by various influences, yet it remains firmly rooted in its cultural origins. Local music festivals and artistic gatherings are cherished moments to celebrate and preserve this unique heritage. The music of Taza continues to resonate in the hearts of its inhabitants, providing a powerful connection to their past and reinforcing their cultural identity in the present.
                        </p>
